$$pqrh = rsr \iff rs^2 \; \text{is} \; 6$$
That is, 
$$\frac{pqr}{2} = r^2 \iff \frac{rs^2}{2} = 6 \iff r^2h = pqr \times 12$$
For some reason, the assumption of $pqr$ and $rs$ is that $rs^2$ is twice of $pqr,$ i.e., $a$ is relatively prime to $b,$ then $b^2 > 2a \iff b > \sqrt{2a}.$

